and (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When James Glover was born in 1413, in Wittersham, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Glover, was 27 and his mother, Jane Alston, was 26. He married Agnes Southwyn in 1435, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 6 February 1456, in his hometown, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1413–6 February 1456":"1413–6. veebruar 1456","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1412–Male":"1412–Surnud","1413–1456":"1413–1456","1415–1456":"1415–1456","1439–1489":"1439–1489","1440–1455":"1440–1455","1443–1489":"1443–1489","1446–Male":"1446–Surnud","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1386–1485":"1386–1485","1387–1486":"1387–1486","6 February 1456":"6. veebruar 1456","1440":"1440","1448":"1448","1415":"1415","1413":"1413","1435":"1435","1446":"1446","1456":"1456","1412":"1412","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1486":"1486","1387":"1387","1485":"1485","1386":"1386","1439":"1439","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Beneden, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Wittersham, Kent, England":"Wittersham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1413–6 February 1456":"1413–6. helmikuuta 1456","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1412–Male":"1412–Kuollut","1413–1456":"14